```Explanations
Thermistor (NTC) - This is the temperature sensing element, an NTC thermistor, which decreases its resistance with an increase in temperature. The NTCLE100E3 is selected for its specific temperature coefficient suitable for the 10-90Â°C range.

Linearizing Resistor - A fixed resistor connected in parallel with the thermistor to linearize its response around the midpoint of the desired temperature range. This improves the accuracy of the measurement across the specified temperature range.

Wheatstone Bridge - A circuit configuration that compares the resistance of the thermistor with the linearizing resistor. It converts the resistance changes into a differential voltage signal, which is more suitable for precise amplification.

Instrumentation Amplifier - A high-precision amplifier used to amplify the small differential voltage from the Wheatstone bridge to a level that can be further processed. It offers high input impedance, low output impedance, and excellent common-mode rejection.

Low-Pass Filter - An analog filter that removes high-frequency noise from the signal to prevent aliasing and to ensure signal fidelity. It serves as an anti-aliasing filter if an ADC is used in the future and provides a cleaner signal for the voltage-to-voltage converter.

Voltage-to-Voltage Converter - This block scales the output of the instrumentation amplifier to the 0-20V range desired for the multimeter reading. The scaling factor is determined by the amplifier gain and the needed output range in relation to the thermistor's temperature-voltage characteristic.

Output Voltage (0-20V) - The final conditioned analog voltage that represents the temperature measurement, which can be read directly using a multimeter. This voltage is linearly related to the temperature of the water in the beaker within the specified range.
